### Configure Astro project with defineConfig

Source: https://context7.com/withastro/astro/llms.txt

The defineConfig function provides a type-safe way to define project settings, including site metadata, build output modes, server adapters, and framework integrations. It is typically used within the astro.config.mjs file to manage the build lifecycle and environment behavior.

```javascript
import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config';
import react from '@astrojs/react';
import node from '@astrojs/node';

export default defineConfig({
  site: 'https://example.com',
  output: 'server',
  adapter: node({ mode: 'standalone' }),
  integrations: [react()],
  server: {
    port: 4321,
    host: true
  },
  i18n: {
    defaultLocale: 'en',
    locales: ['en', 'fr', 'es']
  }
});
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Session Management with Astro.config.mjs

Source: https://context7.com/withastro/astro/llms.txt

Configures server-side session management in Astro by specifying the output format, adapter, and session driver. This example uses the Redis driver for session storage and defines cookie properties and session time-to-live (TTL). Proper configuration is essential for secure and persistent user sessions.

```typescript
// astro.config.mjs - Session configuration
import { defineConfig, sessionDrivers } from 'astro/config';
import node from '@astrojs/node';

export default defineConfig({
  output: 'server',
  adapter: node({ mode: 'standalone' }),
  session: {
    driver: sessionDrivers.redis({
      url: process.env.REDIS_URL
    }),
    cookie: {
      name: 'my-session',
      httpOnly: true,
      secure: true,
      sameSite: 'lax'
    },
    ttl: 60 * 60 * 24 * 7 // 1 week
  }
});
```

--------------------------------

### Implement Server API Endpoints

Source: https://context7.com/withastro/astro/llms.txt

Shows how to define server-side API routes in Astro using the APIRoute interface. These endpoints handle HTTP methods like GET, PUT, and DELETE, interacting with Astro DB and managing response headers, status codes, and authentication.

```typescript
import type { APIRoute } from 'astro';
import { db, Posts, eq } from 'astro:db';

export const GET: APIRoute = async ({ params }) => {
  const post = await db.select().from(Posts).where(eq(Posts.id, params.id!)).get();
  return new Response(JSON.stringify(post), {
    status: 200,
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' }
  });
};

export const prerender = false;
```

### Astro Starter Kit: Hackernews > Server-side rendering (SSR)

Source: https://github.com/withastro/astro/blob/main/examples/hackernews/README.md

This project is configured for Server-side rendering (SSR) using the @astrojs/node adapter, which allows the application to be deployed to Node.js environments. By utilizing an adapter, Astro can tailor the output to specific hosting platforms. Developers can explore additional adapters and deployment strategies by consulting the official Astro deployment documentation to support various hosting environments beyond Node.

